Power engineers of Dnipropetrovsk region have started a unique program to rescue ... stork nests
In the old days, in order to welcome storks to the yard, the villagers installed a wheel from a cart on a high post, and the heavy nest held on well to it.
Such special supports have not been installed for a long time, therefore storks have chosen the poles of power lines - the intertwined branches rest on wires, thanks to which the stork house stands securely.
Grandmother Anya, near whose house in the village of Ivanovka, Petrikovsky district, a stork family has been living for twenty years, began to notice how the nest was settling, despite all the efforts of its inhabitants.
Birds put new twigs on top, and the bottom layer has already sunk between the wires, is about to collapse.
Of course, I feel sorry for the family of storks, which every year nested at the farmstead, hatched and fed three or four chicks over the summer, but I don&#39;t want to be left without light.
As soon as the birds flew away to the warm lands, grandmother Anya called the Tsarichansky Distribution Zone, which owns the support.
And I didn’t even expect that they would react so quickly.
When our specialists arrived in Ivanovka, they were surprised that the nest was still holding, ”said Sergey Berezovsky, technical director of DTEK Dneprooblenergo.
Corrosion began on the wires, which were, in fact, already inside the nest, weighing 150-200 kilograms.
At any moment, the birds could die from an electrical discharge.
And local residents risked being left without electricity due to damage to the wires.
Therefore, line fitters have begun an operation to save the nest, and this is not the first time in our practice.
Scientists-ornithologists from Dnepropetrovsk National University helped, who developed a scheme for transferring the nest.
They also conducted trainings for employees of district networks.
The famous Dnipropetrovsk ornithologist Alexander Ponomarenko consulted power engineers at all stages of nest reconstruction.
To begin with, it was calculated that more than 50 stork &quot;apartments&quot; are in disrepair in the region.
For their reconstruction, special metal platforms were welded, resembling a funnel.
The base was braided with willow branches, and then the old nest was moved there.
According to experts, it is enough to lay the old branches as a base for the birds to recognize the nest and return to it.
Only then the storks themselves will finish building their dwelling.
A month ago, the first nest was reconstructed in the village of Peschanka, Novomoskovsk District.
A new reinforced concrete post was placed next to the electric support and a platform with an old, already inhabited nest was placed on it.
The entire operation cost the power engineers nine thousand hryvnias.
And the other day, the same housewarming took place in the village of Ivanovka, Petrikovsky district, in the courtyard of Anya&#39;s grandmother.
Here the platform was fixed in its original place, only it was raised above the wires.
Bird watchers are sure that cautious, conservative birds will not even notice in the spring that their &quot;apartment&quot; has undergone major repairs.
By the end of the year, the same reconstruction is expected for four more nests in the Pokrovsky and Tsarichansky districts of the Dnipropetrovsk region.
By the way, while some are saving rare birds, others are ruthlessly killing them.
A few days ago, sad news spread throughout the region - in the village of Ust-Kamenka, Apostolovsky district, on the day of the opening of the pheasant hunt, poachers shot a swan family that lived on a local pond for fun.
Noble birds were not at all afraid of people - the locals fed them and did not offend them.
When the villagers, hearing the shots, ran to the pond, four handsome swans were already lying dead on the water.
Now employees of the Apostolovskiy regional police department are trying to find out who shot at the birds listed in the Red Book.
