Jetmakers feud over seat width when large orders are at stake
A bitter dispute has erupted among leading aircraft manufacturers over the width of tourist class seats on long-haul flights, setting the tone for a bitter confrontation at the Dubai Air Show this month.
The controversy revolves around the width of the seats provided on long-haul flights to economy class passengers, whose interests are not always the focus of airlines, while the amount of space allocated to them plays a key role in the claims about the efficiency of the latest aircraft offered by Airbus SAS and Boeing Co.
Airbus this week called for an industry standard that would require seat widths of at least 18 inches (46 cm) in economy class cabins, but its main US rival Boeing says it is up to airlines to decide.
The controversy comes at a time when aircraft manufacturers are competing to sell larger versions of their long-haul twin-engine aircraft, and potentially record orders are expected at an event on November 17-21.
The layout of the rear of the plane - especially whether 9 or 10 people sit in a row - is central to claims about the cost-effectiveness of new &quot;mini-airbus&quot; designs.
Boeing says its revamped 777X will accommodate 406 people, based on more than 17 inches wide economy class seats, with 10 in each row.
Airbus says a competing version of its A350 will carry 350 people in economy class in 18-inch, 9-in-row seats.
The aircraft giants often trade blows on technical issues through advertisements in the professional press.
Airbus is now speaking directly to the public ahead of the Dubai Airshow, where the 777X is expected to lead with over 100 orders.
She recently demonstrated what a new advertising war could be like by showing financiers a slide of three people in a restaurant huddled together, titled &quot;Would you agree to this?&quot;
“Boeing offers long-haul flights in narrower seats than regional turboprop aircraft,” said John Leahy, Airbus sales chief.
With the change in diet, people gain weight, but the plane seats have not changed dramatically.
Between the early 1970s, when the wide-body Boeing 747 set the standard for modern long-distance travel, and the turn of the century, the weight of the average American male between the ages of 40 and 49 increased by 10 percent, according to the US Department of Health.
The average American man in the 21st century has a waist circumference of 39.7 inches, according to statistics from the US Health Service.
Airbus claims its competitor is sticking to the 1950s seating concept, when the average waist circumference of those who were recently dubbed the &quot;jet public&quot; was narrower.
Airbus says it has commissioned research showing that an extra inch in seat width improves sleep quality by 53 percent.
Boeing disputes Airbus&#39; seat size figures and says manufacturers should not get involved in decisions about how airlines balance fares and amenities.
Research shows cabin comfort isn&#39;t just about seat width, she said.
“It really comes down to giving airlines the choice and the ability to do what they think they need to do to be successful,” said Boeing&#39;s cabin specialist Kent Craver.
They do not want us to decide for them what will bring them profit.
They know their business better than anyone else.
For passengers, the issue is more side space, but for suppliers this is increasingly becoming a factor that can affect margins.
Behind this controversy is a race for aircraft orders valued at at least $ 700 billion in catalog prices over the coming decades - enough to change the balance of American to European exports.
As Reuters first reported in July, the seating arrangement is precisely what is fueling the rivalry in the battle between the latest jet aircraft.
Both Airbus and Boeing claim a 20 percent one-seat profitability improvement in their latest twin-engine long-haul models over the market leader in this segment, the 365-seat Boeing 777-300ER.
Boeing&#39;s claims are based in part on a comparison of the 10-seat 777X to the original 9-seat 777 design.
The unit cost benefit is reduced when compared to the current 10-seat layout.
“The reason Boeing is doing this is to squeeze in more seats and make its aircraft more competitive than our designs,” said Kevin Keniston, head of Europe for Airbus Passenger Comfort.
On the other hand, analysts say cabins with full 10-seat rows for the existing 777s indicate that many passengers prefer a tight seating, which can go hand-in-hand with lower fares.
“Eighteen-inch seats would be ideal for passengers, but the reality is that, commercially, Airbus&#39;s offering is driven by the threat from the 777,” said interior designer Mary Kirby, founder and editor of the Runway Girl Network.
Airbus and Boeing do not supply seats, but offer a supplier directory from which airlines can choose.
Traveling jet sellers around the world even carry tape measures with them to check competing layouts.
While touting comfort, all manufacturers also offer super-dense aircraft for low-cost airlines and regional flights.
Airbus is offering the A350 with 10-seat rows, but says it hasn&#39;t sold it yet.
Until recently, Airbus stressed the need for additional cabin modifications, offering wider aisle seats on some of its aircraft.
Without the backing of a single other manufacturer of large, modern aircraft, experts say her call for a new industry standard is unlikely to skyrocket, but may divert attention from the 777X&#39;s wave of sales.
