Mozambique&#39;s Security Concerns Rise Due to Conflict of Powerful People
Under the statue of Zamora Machel, the founding president of Mozambique, gazing down at them, thousands of people gathered in the center of Maputo to chant peace slogans at one of the rare demonstrations here.
“We want the return of peace; we want stability, ”said Vanessa de Susa, chief executive of the investment company.
Fearing for the future of her country, she changed her business suit for a T-shirt emblazoned with the words “We demand security” in Portuguese and joined the crowd on Thursday in the capital&#39;s Independence Square.
For two weeks, there were almost daily reports of clashes between government forces and Renamo - some of the most violent clashes since the ceasefire more than 20 years ago.
Renamo was once a famous rebel movement, backed first by the white authorities of Rhodesia and then by the apartheid South African government as part of an effort to destabilize the country&#39;s independent government.
After the 1992 ceasefire, it became an opposition party.
Analysts believe that the country is unlikely to slide back into full-scale conflict, but recent events have made foreign investors and local residents nervous.
The stakes are high for a fast-growing economy, as the discovery of huge offshore gas and coal reserves in the northwest could attract more than $ 50 billion in investments over the next few years from companies like Rio Tinto, Vale from Brazil, Eni from Italy, and Anadarko from the United States. ...
The ruling Frelimo party, a leading political force since 1975, and Renamo&#39;s party blame each other for the resulting tensions.
Renamo&#39;s party claims that the government was the instigator of the latest clashes by attacking its members in Sofala province, the traditional stronghold of Renamo, on 17 October.
Attacks on former insurgents then escalated when government forces attacked Renamo bases and attempted to assassinate Afonso Dhlakama, the group&#39;s leader, Fernando Mazanga, a spokesman for Renamo, told the Financial Times.
The government blames Renamo for initiating the clashes, accusing the party of attacking soldiers.
President Armando Guebuza has tried to allay fears of instability.
Guebuza told AFP, the French news agency, on Wednesday that Mr. Dhlakama felt like a &quot;failure&quot; to use &quot;whatever was left of his power to try to prove that he could impose his own decisions on the government.&quot;
Both Frelimo and Renamo insist that they want to avoid war.
However, concerns grew after reports that Mazanga had announced Renamo&#39;s withdrawal from the 1992 peace agreement.
He told the Financial Times that he was referring to the non-compliance by Frelimo&#39;s party.
“Our goal is to get back to negotiations, but with all seriousness,” Mazanga said.
Previous inter-party talks have done little to defuse tensions that have been exacerbated by a series of clashes this year.
“These are two influential people (Gebuza and Dhlakama) facing each other,” said Joseph Hanlon, a lecturer at the Open University and an expert on Mozambique.
None of them is a good negotiator and none of them is willing to make the necessary concessions.
Renamo&#39;s party, which is trying to push for electoral reforms, has already announced that it will boycott the municipal elections scheduled for November.
Presidential and parliamentary elections are scheduled for next year.
Some commentators interpreted the pressure as an attempt by the weakened movement to win concessions and financial bonuses from the government.
The share of votes for Renamo has been declining since 1992, while the new party, the Democratic Movement of Mozambique (MDM), which was founded by a former member of Renamo, is expected to improve its performance in this election.
Mr Mazanga says Mr Gebuza, who is due to step down next year when his second term ends, wants to destroy democracy in the country.
“He doesn&#39;t want multi-party democracy, he doesn&#39;t want transparent elections, he doesn&#39;t want peace because he doesn&#39;t want to leave the presidency,&quot; Mazanga said.
It is unclear what capabilities Renamo has, but she has already carried out devastating and rapid attacks on police stations and vehicles on a key north-south highway.
Most of the skirmishes took place in Sofala province, which is a few hundred kilometers north of Maputo but includes Beira, a port that mining companies including Rio Tinto and Vale use to export coal.
In June, Rio suspended the use of the railroad tracks for about a week after Renamo threatened to attack the railroad.
Mazanga was evasive when asked if Renamo would repeat this threat.
Renamo&#39;s party wanted to “warn the international community that things are not going well in Mozambique,” Mazanga said.
The instability has heightened discontent with the government, and many people are also worried about corruption, the slow pace of development and the recent increase in kidnappings, said Fernando Lima, head of independent media company Mediacoop.
“People think that the government and the president are responsible for the future of the country, and the president must find a solution to these problems,” he says.
Omar Sultuan, a demonstrator, said people just want stability.
“No one cares about Renamo or Frelimo, they just want peace to resume, they want free access to the roads,” he said.
Australia Aircraft Regulations Remain in Force for the Time being
Australian airline passengers will need to continue to turn off their tablets and smartphones during take-off and landing, despite measures in the United States to relax the rules regarding these devices.
The US Federal Aviation Administration has allowed US carriers to change their procedures so that passengers can read e-books, watch videos or play games on their devices during takeoff and landing, provided they remain in Airplane Mode.
Passengers can already do this during the main part of the flight, but many are annoyed that they do not have access to their e-books during takeoff and landing.
Australian carriers are considering the move, which required US airlines to do a huge amount of work to meet the new requirements, but indicated that they do not plan to change their procedures in the near future.
The Civil Aviation Safety Administration also noted that they are considering this application, but stressed that restrictions on the use of electronic devices during critical phases of flight are still in force in Australia.
“The Civil Aviation Safety Administration currently does not have specific regulations governing the use of electronic devices on aircraft,” it said.
This issue is governed by rules that require air carriers to ensure the maintenance of security at all times, and from passengers - to comply with the safety rules that are communicated to them by the crew.
Virgin, which has already discussed with the Civil Aviation Safety Authority about expanding on-board use of its Wi-Fi entertainment system, was not opposed to the change, but said it would follow the regulator&#39;s instructions.
“We would welcome consideration by the Civil Aviation Safety Authority of allowing the use of electronic devices, because we really think it will improve the customer experience now that we have it (in-flight wireless entertainment) on our aircraft,” said a spokesman. ...
Qantas said it will adhere to the current regulations.
“Our current policy is that electronic devices cannot be used during takeoff and landing, and we do not plan to change it anytime soon,” she said.
The FAA regulation applies to American airlines.
However, we are always interested in regulatory changes that could benefit passengers, and we will certainly be looking closely at the FAA&#39;s decision and the reasons behind it.
For US carriers, the impact of the regulation will vary from airline to airline and will depend on the age of their fleet.
Carriers will have to prove their aircraft is immune to radio interference from mobile devices, and review manuals, training materials, carry-on baggage regulations and passenger instructions.
“Once the airline has verified and confirmed the immunity of its fleet, it can allow passengers to use portable, lightweight electronic devices such as tablets, e-readers and smartphones at any altitude,” the FAA said.
In the rare event of poor visibility, the crew will instruct passengers to turn off their devices during boarding.
