Scientists have shed light on how a dog&#39;s tail movement is related to its mood.
Earlier studies have shown that happy dogs wag their tail to the right (from a dog&#39;s point of view), while anxious dogs wag their tail predominantly to the left.
But now scientists say other canids can notice and respond to these subtle differences in tail wagging.
Professor Giorgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trent, says: &quot;It is well known that in humans, the left and right sides of the brain are involved in different ways in the formation of stimuli that cause positive or negative emotions.&quot;
Here we tried to look at this in other species as well.
He added that just like in humans, in dogs, the right side of the brain controls the left side of the body and vice versa, and the two hemispheres play different roles in emotion.
To learn more about how dogs respond to other dogs&#39; versatile tail wagging, the researchers observed the animals while they watched films about other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of the animals and analyzed their behavior.
Probably, soon we will understand why their tails sometimes go one way, and sometimes the other.
Professor Vallortigara said: &quot;We showed dogs videos of dogs - either naturalistic versions or silhouette, to get rid of any other distortions, and we could manipulate the movement of the tail and direct the tail more to the left or right.&quot;
When the animals saw that the otherwise expressionless dog moved its tail to the right (from the point of view of a dog wagging its tail), they remained completely relaxed.
But when they noticed that the tail was tilting predominantly to the left (again from the point of view of the dog wagging the tail), their heart rate increased and they looked alarmed.
Professor Vallortigara said he doesn&#39;t think the dogs intentionally communicated with each other through these movements.
In fact, he believes that dogs have learned from experience which movements they should worry about and which ones they shouldn&#39;t.
He notes: &quot;If there are several encounters with other dogs and often wagging their tail to one side is associated with friendlier behavior, and the right side gives less friendly behavior, then the dog will react based on this experience.&quot;
The researchers say these results could give owners, veterinarians and trainers a deeper understanding of their pet&#39;s emotions.
Dog behavior expert John Bradshaw, a visiting fellow at the University of Bristol Veterinary School, said this was not the first study to test whether left and right sides mattered in dogs.
Last year, a team of scientists from the University of Lincoln found that dogs turn their heads to the left when looking at an aggressive dog and to the right when looking at a contented dog.
And in another research paper from the University of Victoria in Canada, he reported: &quot;Dogs were more likely to approach a robotic dog when its tail wagged to the left rather than to the right, instead of becoming anxious — the opposite of an Italian study.&quot;
He said the differences could be because dogs in various studies did not fully perceive animals in films or robotic dogs as dogs.
Research into how dogs respond to real dogs could be helpful, he explained.
“While there is ample evidence for different mammals that the two hemispheres of the brain are used for different purposes, many details remain to be clarified, and dogs are no exception,” he said.
However, given the ease with which their behavior can be recorded, we will probably soon understand why their tails sometimes go one way and sometimes the other.
