Ride through mud, rivers and jungle for free medical care
Dr. Georges Bwellet Provides Free Rural Health Care in Cameroon
Bvelle and his team spend almost every weekend, seeing hundreds of patients
There are not many doctors in this West African country - only one in 5000 people.
Vote here or via your mobile device
Dr. Georges Bvelle is one of the 10 main characters of CNN 2013.
You can vote for him or any of the other 10 main characters to become CNN Hero of the Year.
This person will receive $ 250,000 to continue his outstanding work.
For 21 years, Georges Bvellet saw his father come back to life and fall into unconsciousness again, wandering through hospitals that were not properly equipped to help him.
Jamef Bwelle was injured in a car accident in 1981 near Yaounde, the capital of Cameroon.
At first, he only had a broken arm, but the resulting infection spread to the brain and caused a hematoma, which reminded of itself for the rest of his life.
“There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon,” said Georges Bvelle.
If we had the money, we would have taken him out of Cameroon.
Instead, Bwelle accompanied his father to overcrowded clinics and hospitals for years, receiving whatever treatment they could get.
“It&#39;s not easy,” Bwelle said.
- You can leave home at 5 am, run to the hospital to be the first, but you are not the first.
There are a lot of patients.
Some may die because they have to wait.
The situation hasn&#39;t changed much since Bvelle&#39;s father passed away in 2002.
According to the World Health Organization, Cameroon has only one doctor in 5,000 people.
By comparison, the ratio in the United States is one doctor in 413 people.
And even if Cameroonians could see a doctor, many of them would not be able to afford it.
Two out of five people in this country live below the poverty line, and almost three quarters of health care spending is private.
“Their only problem is poverty,” Bwelle said.
&quot;And because of poverty, they cannot enjoy their lives.&quot;
Seeing the suffering of his father and so many of his compatriots, Bwelle was determined to do something about it.
Last year, Dr. Georges Bvellet and his team of volunteers performed 700 free surgeries.
He became a physician himself and works as a vascular surgeon at Yaounde Central Hospital.
He also founded the non-profit organization ASCOVIME, which organizes weekend trips to the countryside to provide free medical care.
Since 2008, he and his group of volunteers have helped nearly 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, he and up to 30 others stuff vans, strap medical supplies to rooftops, and drive cross-country to visit villages in need.
They are not always lucky.
More than once they had to push cars across rivers and mud.
But when they arrive, they are greeted like real heroes: a celebration of songs and dances and the best accommodations the locals have to offer.
The free medical care in these villages is truly cause for celebration, and Bvelle, with his wide smile and boundless energy, is more than happy to join in the fun.
The next morning, the team begins to see hundreds of patients.
“We host 500 people on every trip,” Bwelle said.
They come from all over the area within a 60-kilometer radius of the village, and they come on foot.
Each of these weekend clinics provides a variety of medical services.
Many people receive treatment for malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others may receive crutches, donated glasses or free birth certificates - documents needed for school that many poor families simply cannot afford.
In the evenings, the team performs simple surgeries under local anesthesia.
Operations are usually carried out in a school building, municipality or home; after the procedure, patients get up and go to the postoperative area to make room for the next person.
Using a generator to light the operating room and sanitize equipment, Bwelle and his volunteers work until early Sunday morning.
It&#39;s an unbearable pace, but the team&#39;s sense of purpose is usually helped by the village musicians.
“They beat drums all night to keep us awake and keep working,” Bwelle said.
On Sunday, the crew members head back to town, tired but proud of their work.
This group of Cameroonian doctors and international medical students has performed 700 free surgeries over the past year, and they know their help can make a huge difference to those they help.
One person explained that the free hernia surgery he received would allow him to work again.
“It will change the future for me and my family,” the man said.
In addition to these weekend clinical appointments and hospital work, Bwelle&#39;s surgeon also works overnight in private medical clinics around Yaounde.
It is this second job, he says, that provides 60% of the funding for his non-profit organization; the rest is covered by private donations.
“I don&#39;t even know when he sleeps,” said Katie O&#39;Malley, a second-year medical student at Drexel University in Philadelphia and a volunteer in the Bwelle group.
He is always either in the hospital or trying to raise money for the organization so that these campaigns can continue.
For future doctors and nurses like O&#39;Malley coming from the US and Europe to join Bwelle in his mission, this is a practice opportunity that they would never have received at home.
“We were able to assist in surgeries where we helped remove blood stains or hold instruments for Dr. Bwelle,” O&#39;Malley said.
As a sophomore, you would never get an opportunity like this in America.
Student volunteers usually pay for their own travel to Cameroon, often arriving with donated medicines.
But upon arrival in Yaounde, Bvelle pays for their food, transport and tuition.
“He&#39;s a hero, no doubt about it,” said O&#39;Malley.
