Goldman Sachs warned of risks for the Russian economy
Goldman Sachs warned of growing risks to the main driver of fragile economic growth in Russia - consumption.
First of all, this is the crisis of non-payment of unsecured consumer loans and massive layoffs of workers.
Our main concern right now is not that growth has slowed down, but rather the structure of that growth.
Recently, it has been entirely driven by consumption, which has hardly slowed down, &quot;said Clemens Grafé, chief economist at Goldman Sachs for Russia, presenting the investment bank&#39;s quarterly report on the Russian economy yesterday.
Now the nominal growth of wages in Russia is about 10%.
With inflation of 6%, it will be able to provide future consumer demand at roughly current levels, Goldman Sachs expects.
But the profitability of Russian companies is falling, so, most likely, they will focus on optimizing personnel costs.
Today we see a significant increase in the share of wages in GDP: if wages grow by 10%, then GDP - only by 2%, - explained Mr. Grafe.
Companies have faced declining margins.
If it does not grow, it can lead to layoffs and an increase in unemployment.
Russian business cannot but raise wages, says Vladimir Pantyushin, chief economist at Barclays Capital for Russia and the CIS.
Unemployment is near historic lows, and competition for workers is high.
In order to lure outside employees or keep the current ones, employers have to raise wages.
Consumption in Russia is also supported by a very rapid growth in consumer lending.
According to Mr. Grafe, this type of lending does not have a multiplier effect on the country&#39;s economy due to extremely high rates on consumer loans.
&quot;We did not see any benefits for the economy from the growth of consumer lending, the money does not go through the economy, but returns to the same banks in the form of interest payments,&quot; the economist said.
But the problem is different - Goldman Sachs expects an increase in delinquency on unsecured loans.
They are taken mostly by poor people who have nothing to provide as security.
Interest on such loans is high.
As a result, they are often not returned, &quot;said Mr. Grafe.
Therefore, the second threat to economic growth in Russia is a possible crisis of non-payment of unsecured loans.
Vasily Solodkov, director of the HSE Banking Institute, already sees signs of a looming banking crisis.
Small credit institutions, not having access to cheap resources, which state banks have, were forced to attract funds from the population at high interest rates.
In response, state banks went on the warpath and began to reduce lending rates, - continues the economist.
Small credit institutions cannot issue loans at the same interest rate, otherwise they will have a negative interest margin.
If state banks do not give up dumping, Russia will face a full-fledged banking crisis, believes Vasily Solodkov.
The economist considers the revocation of licenses of a number of banks in recent weeks to be a harbinger of a massive collapse.
&quot;The state banks themselves will not cope with this situation: the deposit insurance system was not originally designed for a systemic crisis,&quot; warns the head of the institute.
But the growth of consumption will slow down even without the crisis of non-payments, the investment bank believes, due to the refusal to index the salaries of civil servants and military personnel, which is included in the current version of the draft budget.
The blow to consumption will be partially mitigated by the freezing of tariffs by natural monopolies (and, as a consequence, by lower inflation).
But only partially: if investments do not grow (and there are no prerequisites for this yet - see the reference), consumption growth will still slow down, Goldman Sachs is sure.
Vladimir Pantyushin from Barclays Capital does not yet see the prerequisites for the implementation of pessimistic scenarios.
&quot;The main risk is still a drop in oil prices,&quot; he says.
According to him, the Russian economy will begin to shrink when oil prices are below $ 90 per barrel.
Goldman Sachs also noted that the Central Bank is not yet able to reduce interest rates in the economy.
A paradoxical picture is observed: inflation has decreased, and banks have begun to raise rates.
This may mean that they did not believe the Central Bank, which announced the transition to inflation targeting, &quot;said Clemens Grafe.
The interest rate policy of the Central Bank does not affect market rates, only affects the rates of interbank lending.
&quot;For the Central Bank, this is the collapse of all hopes,&quot; said Clemens Grafe.
The money received at the Central Bank&#39;s auctions is used by banks not for lending to the economy, but for managing their liquidity
As soon as the rate decreases, the exchange rate immediately changes, which means that the funds are trying to go to speculation against the ruble.
&quot;Sooner or later, the Central Bank will understand that this strategy does not work,&quot; said Mr. Grafe and recalled that the state plans to let the ruble &quot;float freely&quot; by the end of 2015.
But we will either have to do it earlier, or raise the key rate of the Central Bank (5.5%), he said.
According to him, the ruble exchange rate is now artificially overvalued by 10%.
There is only one way to ruble - to weaken, - the expert concludes.
But if the Central Bank sows in the financiers even a shadow of doubt that the elimination of the currency corridor is not part of a policy to weaken the ruble, this could bring down the ruble much more.
