FAA: &quot;Air passengers can now use gadgets on planes (but not call from a mobile phone)&quot;
Air passengers will be able to use their electronic devices throughout the flight to read, work, play games, watch movies and listen to music, but not talk on their mobile phones, according to long-awaited new guidelines released Thursday by the Federal Aviation Administration.
But passengers shouldn&#39;t expect changes to happen immediately.
How quickly such a change is implemented will vary by airline, FAA Administrator Michael Huerta said at a news conference.
Airlines will have to show the FAA how their aircraft are meeting the new guidelines and that they are updating their flight crew training manuals and stowage regulations to comply with the new guidelines.
The FAA said it has already received plans from some airlines to expand the use of portable electronic devices on airplanes.
Delta and JetBlue were among the airlines that have already submitted plans.
“Depending on the state of the plan, we could approve an increase in the use of electronic devices very soon,” the FAA said.
Currently, passengers are required to turn off their smartphones, tablets and other devices as soon as the plane door closes.
They should not restart them until the aircraft reaches 10,000 feet and the captain gives the go-ahead.
Passengers must turn off their devices again when the plane descends for landing, and do not turn them on until the plane is on the ground.
Under the new guidelines, airlines whose aircraft are adequately protected from electronic interference may allow passengers to use these devices during takeoff, landing and taxiing, the FAA said.
Most new airliners and other aircraft modified to allow passengers to use Wi-Fi at high altitudes are expected to meet these criteria.
Laura Glading, President of the Professional Flight Attendants Association, welcomed the change.
“Once the new policy is successfully implemented (and we are going to work closely with the carrier to achieve this), it will be a win-win,” said Glading.
We are frankly tired of feeling like “school attendants” when it comes to this issue.
But Internet connections for surfing, e-mailing, texting or downloading data will still be banned below 10,000 feet, the agency said.
Passengers will be prompted to switch their smartphones, tablets and other devices to airplane mode.
Thus, there are still no Words with Friends, an intellectual Internet game that actor Alec Baldwin played on his smartphone in 2011, when a sensational incident occurred: the actor was removed from an American Airlines plane for refusing to turn off the device. the time the plane was at the gate.
And heavier devices, such as laptops, will still need to be stowed in the luggage compartment, as they can injure someone if they fly around the cabin.
In-flight calls from a mobile phone will also continue to be prohibited.
Regulatory authority over phone calls rests with the FCC, not the FAA.
FAA may lift ban on certain electronic devices during takeoff and landing
Mark Rosenker of the National Transportation Safety Board and national transportation safety expert for CBS News said last month that cell phones are still considered a risk.
“Cell phones are really a problem, not only because they have the potential to interfere with navigation devices, but we know from the FCC that they can interfere with cell towers when the plane is in the air,” Rosenker said.
An industry advisory committee, set up by the FAA to look into the matter, recommended last month that the government allow wider use of personal electronic devices.
In recent years, there has been mounting pressure on the FAA to ease restrictions on their use.
Critics such as Missouri Democratic Senator Claire McCaskill argue that there is no compelling security reason for the bans.
Compliance is also becoming increasingly difficult to enforce as the use of devices has become ubiquitous.
Some studies show that up to a third of passengers forget or ignore instructions to turn off their devices.
The FAA began restricting passenger use of electronic devices in 1966 in response to reports of interference with navigation and communications equipment, when passengers began carrying around FM radios, the high-tech gadgets of the day.
New airliners are much more dependent on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also being developed and approved by the FAA to be immune to electronic interference.
Airlines have been offering passengers Wi-Fi at cruising altitude for several years.
Airplanes modified for Wi-Fi systems are also more immune to interference.
The vast majority of liners are geared towards wider electronic use under the new guidelines, Huerta said.
Today&#39;s electronic devices typically emit radio signals at a much lower power than previous generations of devices.
E-book readers, for example, emit only minimal signals when flipping through pages.
But signals become more powerful when devices are downloading or sending data.
Among those pushing for relaxation of restrictions on the use of electronic devices by passengers was Amazon.com.
In 2011, company officials loaded an entire airliner with their Kindle e-readers and flew around to check for problems, but never found them.
FAA advisory committee members expressed mixed feelings about whether the devices present any risk.
Douglas Kidd of the National Air Passengers Association said he considers interference from devices to be real, even if the risk is minimal.
Other committee members said that there are only sporadic reports from pilots confirming that devices can interfere with aircraft systems, and most of these reports are very old.
However, the committee recommended that the FAA allow pilots to require passengers to disable devices during instrument landings in low visibility conditions.
A travel industry group hailed the change, calling it a sensible move to accommodate passengers who now use a variety of technological devices.
“We are pleased that the FAA recognizes that passenger comfort is not incompatible with safety and security,” said Roger Doe, CEO of the United States Travel Association.
