New anti-nicotine vaccine could rob the pleasure of smoking
Scientists have developed an anti-nicotine vaccine that could take away the pleasure of smoking cigarettes.
One dose of the vaccine was able to protect mice from nicotine addiction for life.
Further tests are needed before human trials begin, which will take several years, but Professor Ronald Crystal of Weill Cornell College of Medicine in New York said the first results were encouraging.
“We really hope that this vaccine strategy can finally help the millions of smokers who have tried to quit by trying every method on the market today, but have found that their nicotine addiction is strong enough to overcome it with these modern remedies.” Professor Cornell said.
The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that was designed to carry the genetic information for the production of anti-nicotine antibodies.
The virus selectively infects liver cells, which then begin to produce a steady stream of antibodies.
The antibodies track down any nicotine molecules in the blood, neutralizing them before they reach the brain, preventing smokers from getting a nicotine hit.
In tests, vaccinated mice that were subsequently given nicotine continued their normal activities.
And mice that were not given the vaccine &quot;relaxed,&quot; a sign that the nicotine was reaching their brains, the researchers say.
These experiments are described in the journal Science Translational Medicine.
Previous tobacco vaccines have failed because they contained antibodies.
To keep antibody levels high, injections had to be given so often that they were expensive and impractical.
But the cost of the new vaccine is likely to be much lower because it turns liver cells into antibody factories.
Professor Crystal said that if the future human vaccine were completely safe, it could be given to children before they have the urge to try a cigarette, preventing nicotine addiction.
But it is more likely that it will be used by smokers to quit smoking.
“They will know that if they start smoking again, they will not get the pleasure of the nicotine vaccine, and this can help them get rid of this habit,” he said.
The British scientists said the results were interesting, but cautioned that more research was needed.
