Rosbalt agency stripped of media status for obscene language
On October 31, the Moscow City Court ruled to invalidate the license to register the Rosbalt agency, writes Lenta.
Roskomnadzor insisted on depriving the agency of its media status for systematic and gross violations of the law on the media.
During the process, an unpleasant precedent was created: the court considered it possible to close the media outlets, in fact, denying the publication the right to put forward counterarguments.
What is Rosbalt
CJSC &quot;Information Agency Rosbalt&quot; was established in St. Petersburg in 2000.
In subsequent years, the agency opened a second head office in Moscow and a number of regional divisions.
The agency also has representative offices in the countries of the former USSR.
Since 2001, Rosbalt has developed and functioned as a federal information and analytical agency.
By the mid-2000s, the agency was on the list of the most recognizable private Internet media in Russia.
At the same time, Rosbalt has always occupied a rather specific niche: the core of the agency&#39;s exclusive publications was (and still are) notes with reference to sources in law enforcement agencies.
Talk about the publication&#39;s proximity to the security forces continued throughout the agency&#39;s existence.
Along with the fact that Rosbalt had an extensive base of sources in various departments, the fact that Natalya Chaplina, the wife of Viktor Cherkesov, was at the head of the project, also spoke in favor of such assumptions.
At the same time, Chaplina&#39;s role in the management of Rosbalt is not completely clear: most often she is called the &quot;project manager&quot;.
The general director of the agency is Larisa Afonina, the chief editor is Nikolay Ulyanov.
Recently, Rosbalt has not appeared in the ratings of the federal media - neither in terms of citation, nor in terms of audience.
In October, the agency took 25th place in the rating of traffic on Russian media sites according to LiveInternet.
According to the same LiveInternet, the average daily audience of rosbalt.ru is about 150 thousand unique visitors (and up to 500 thousand views), the monthly audience is about three million unique visitors.
Among the most popular materials over the past five months are notes about the Kremlin&#39;s helplessness in relations with Ukraine, the death of the lead singer of the &quot;King and the Jester&quot; group, and pogroms in the capital Biryulyovo.
The conflict between Rosbalt and Roskomnadzor began in July 2013, when amendments to the law on mass media came into force, banning foul language on journalists.
The agency found prohibited vocabulary in two videos published on the agency&#39;s website (&quot;Dzhigit from Krasnodar&quot; and &quot;Pussy Riot defiled oil rigs&quot;).
Further sides are described in different ways.
Roskomnadzor, on the basis of the video footage found, accused Rosbalt of gross and systematic violation of the law on mass media and went to court demanding to revoke the agency&#39;s license.
Rosbalt stated that the agency&#39;s claims were inappropriate: firstly, the videos were not editorial materials, secondly, the obscene words in them were disguised, and, thirdly, immediately after the warning, the videos were removed from the site.
Representatives of the agency appealed the claims of Roskomnadzor in the magistrates&#39; court - and when on October 22, 2013 the Moscow City Court accepted the claim of Roskomnadzor, the consideration of these complaints was still ongoing.
However, on the 25th, the magistrate made a decision not in favor of Rosbalt: the editor-in-chief Nikolai Ulyanov was found guilty of violating the Code of Administrative Offenses and was fined 20 thousand rubles - 10 thousand for each video.
Obviously, this predetermined the outcome of the hearing in the Moscow City Court - if we abandon the idea that the outcome could have been predetermined even earlier.
On October 31, the court ruled to invalidate Rosbalt&#39;s registration certificate, effectively depriving the agency of its media status.
It cannot be said that Rosbalt remained alone during this confrontation.
The agency was supported by State Duma deputies (a statement addressed to the head of Roskomnadzor, Alexander Zharov, was signed on October 10 by 26 deputies; the document itself was submitted at the initiative of the Communist Party of the Russian Federation).
The head of the Union of Journalists of Russia Vsevolod Bogdanov, the chairman of the Moscow Union of Journalists Pavel Gusev and the head of the Presidential Council for Human Rights Mikhail Fedotov stated that the publication was unlawful.
Moreover, according to Bogdanov, the leadership of Roskomnadzor even provided him with some guarantees that it would not come to the revocation of the license.
The trial of Rosbalt showed that under whose jurisdiction it is safer for the media to be in Russia today is a big question.
