George Kerevan: the break with Europe gives the Scots a choice
Another day, another horror story about independence.
This time we are being warned that an independent Scotland will have to join the pan-European free movement area as a condition of EU membership.
It is the turn of the stories about passport control in Berwick and the barbed wire border along Hadrian&#39;s Wall.
True, the Strathclyde newspaper pointed to the possible economic benefits of freer movement across the rest of Europe, although - predictably - it didn&#39;t make headlines.
Nor has anyone pointed out that EU member states spend a lot of time twisting their formal rules to suit them.
Since Scotland is not currently part of the Schengen area, continued non-compliance would be a cheap concession for Brussels in return for what it really wanted the Scots to do.
So this is not a worthy story.
And so old that it turned into a fossil: the first time I heard the &quot;duck&quot; that &quot;independence means passport control&quot;, at least 40 years ago.
And yet there is an interesting moment lost in the retelling of an old tale.
Why should an independent Scotland obey Europe&#39;s orders at all?
Why exchange the yoke of London for the yoke of Brussels, especially now?
Here&#39;s the real European news: The great post-war plan to unify Europe has finally stalled.
With the euro crisis, the Europe project is officially dead.
Across the European Union, parties opposed to the EU or to abolish the euro as a single currency are gaining ground.
Even in Germany, the Eurosceptic Alternative for Germany party - founded just this year - came out of nowhere and won nearly five million votes in the September federal elections, thus effectively ousting the Free Democrats (analogous to our Liberal Democrats) from the Bundestag ...
There has always been internal opposition to the plan for a federal Europe.
Nonetheless, the current economic crisis has become a turning point.
The austerity measures imposed by Berlin and the European Central Bank, and the shackles imposed on national economies through the preservation of a single currency, have led many people to believe that Project Europe has gone too far.
The euro crisis has little to do with national governments operating with excessive budget deficits - this was only true for Greece.
In fact, the Eurosystem has locked its members on exchange rates favorable to German exporters - which German politicians want to keep.
Without the possibility of devaluation of the national currency, southern Europe finds itself in a preliminary disadvantage in terms of production capabilities in comparison with Germany.
The only lifesaver is to cut wages and government spending, which is actively supported by Berlin.
Behind the current budget and currency problems lies the deeper problem of Europe&#39;s productive capacity.
As a result of the green energy package implemented by Brussels - a cipher that subsidizes French and German energy companies at the expense of the consumer - European industry pays twice as much for electricity and four times as much for gas as in the US.
This is a paralyzing unfavorable price environment, as we saw in Grangemouth.
No amount of global wage freezes will stop the crushing victory of cheap US shale gas over the European petrochemical industry.
As a result, a riot is brewing, especially in France, once the EU&#39;s most ardent supporter.
After the war, the French political elite saw the EU as a way to control Germany and put Paris on a par with Washington.
But Berlin no longer needs Paris as a vehicle for political legitimacy, and has already imposed its own economic policies on Europe, leaving France&#39;s shattered economy in dire straits.
The result is that the right-wing, anti-EU National Front party, Marine Le Pen, has just won a decisive by-election, dropping the ruling Socialist Party in third place.
The Front is now the most popular party in France with 24 percent of the vote - a timely warning to British Labor not to assume that a split among the right will automatically favor the left.
What is Le Pen doing with her newfound popularity among the French white working class?
She wants to use next year&#39;s EU elections to create a bloc in the European Parliament against the EU and against the common currency.
If - and this is very likely - anti-EU parties gain support in these elections, such a bloc could for the first time take a dominant position in the European Parliament.
Here&#39;s my opinion: Soon the growing anti-EU and anti-common currency sentiment in Europe will merge to destroy the euro.
The EU will not disappear, but it will once again become something of the vague &quot;Europe of (sovereign) nations&quot; that General de Gaulle liked.
Germany and several economies dependent on it could keep the euro, but France and southern Europe will recover their own currencies.
My guess is that the UK is distancing itself from this project, hoping to get closer to the US.
Nonetheless, Washington&#39;s growing interest in the Pacific indicates the likelihood of Britain being left behind in the cold Atlantic.
In what position does this leave Scotland?
We may choose to become a region of (essentially) Little England.
Or we can defend our own economic interests, which means, among other things, send Berlin and Brussels to hell.
I suspect that Scotland can do well with a freer European deal, provided we keep our currency.
Cooperation with other like-minded countries will be easier in the non-federal Europe of nations.
