Early puberty: aging earlier
African American and Latino girls tend to reach puberty earlier than their white counterparts, studies show.
Physical changes don&#39;t mean puberty is near
No evidence that hormones or other chemicals are to blame
Experts believe the obesity epidemic may be one of the triggers of early puberty
The trend towards early puberty is less pronounced in boys
Former CNN correspondent Pat Etheridge is a journalist specializing in children&#39;s health and family issues.
Should a mother be intimidated if her daughter begins to form the rudiments of the mammary gland and grow pubic hair at 7 or 8 years old?
At the annual conference of the American Academy of Pediatrics this week in Orlando, Florida, pediatric endocrinologist Dr. Paul Kaplowitz explained that these early physical changes are quite common among American girls and represent the new normal.
“I spend a lot of time reassuring my parents — that usually doesn&#39;t mean full puberty quickly,” Kaplowitz said.
Obvious signs of development, such as growing breasts, pubic and axillary hair, and body odor, appear earlier in girls.
But there has only been a slight shift in the age of menarche (first menstruation) over the past four decades.
In the United States, the median age is 12.5 years old, down from 12.75 in 1970.
“Once breasts begin to develop, it is at least two to three years before menarche,” said Kaplowitz, who is also the author of Early Puberty in Girls: Coping with This Common Problem.
Time is the most accurate test of how puberty will progress.
There is debate about what constitutes the actual onset of puberty, but is considered “premature” when breast augmentation is accompanied by a sharp increase in height up to 8 years.
In most cases, the process will slow down or pause - this is something that the pediatrician can monitor closely.
Faster progression may warrant testing by an endocrinologist to rule out serious problems such as tumors or cysts.
There are treatments to delay early menstruation and prevent another consequence: premature aging of the bones, which can ultimately lead to stunted growth and stunted growth in adulthood.
Recommendations for drug or hormone therapy are based on the child&#39;s age, developmental level, growth rate, and emotional maturity.
The psychosocial aspects are also important.
Kaplowitz is cautious with medications, but admits that &quot;suppressing puberty can alleviate the behavioral problems and feelings of girls that they are different from their peers.&quot;
Another big problem is clear: Parents simply don&#39;t want their very young daughters to have periods.
“They worry about the risk of pregnancy or even how they will handle hygiene issues,” Kaplowitz said.
“It was a shock,” recalls one woman, whose daughter started menstruating at age 10.
Although there were signs and we talked about her period, she was not emotionally ready.
She came home from school terrified and upset that she was the first among her friends.
There are many highly publicized theories about the causes of early puberty.
However, there is no consistent evidence that hormones in milk or other foods, chemicals in the environment, or sexual messages in the media are to blame.
In boys - as in girls - puberty occurs earlier.
Kaplowitz argues that the premise that carries the most weight is the obesity epidemic.
In 2001, he helped conduct a study of girls aged 6 to 9 that linked body fat to the timing of puberty.
Other evidence supports this conclusion, but there are many other contributing factors.
In this country, African American and Latino girls tend to reach puberty earlier than their white counterparts.
There are various explanations.
Around the world, early puberty appears to be influenced by everything from economic conditions and climate to genes.
Another mystery: Although boys develop facial and pubic hair at a younger age, the tendency towards full early puberty is not as pronounced as in girls.
Other physicians attending the AAP conference confirmed the complexity of this topic.
The appearance of acne and pubic hair occurs even in babies and toddlers.
“We have to be careful about how we define true onset of puberty,” said Dr. Lawrence Silverman, pediatric endocrinologist at Gorieb Children&#39;s Hospital in Morristown, NJ.
Parents should feel free to get directions from a pediatrician on how to talk to their child.
“This could mean an earlier conversation than expected,” Kaplowitz explained.
If you remain calm, your child will usually respond well.
Girls who bloom early need reassurance that even when it happens early, the process is a normal part of life.
