Nevada is one of several states struggling to find low-cost technology that would allow state governments to keep track of miles traveled by a car, but without information about the place and time.
If you can do this, Khan said, society will feel more relaxed.
The quest for this technology led some state agencies to a small fledgling company in California called True Mileage.
This company was not originally involved in helping to collect state taxes.
She aimed to enter the emerging market for a form of car insurance in which drivers pay on a mileage basis.
But the devices she tests appeal to road planners because they don&#39;t use GPS and provide a limited amount of information that is periodically downloaded via a modem.
“People will be more likely to do this if you don&#39;t track their speed and location,” said Ryan Morrison, CEO of True Mileage.
There were some big mistakes in some of these state pilot programs.
There are much less expensive and less intrusive ways to do this.
In Oregon, designers are experimenting with giving drivers different options.
They can choose a device with or without GPS.
Or they might ditch the device altogether, choosing instead to pay a flat fee based on the average miles driven by all residents in the state.
Elsewhere, they hope to sell the idea to a wary public by forcing devices to do more, not less.
In New York City, transportation officials are looking to develop a taxation device that will also accept payment for parking meters, provide pay-as-you-drive insurance, and collect a pool of real-time speed data from other drivers that motorists could use to avoid traffic jams.
&quot;Motorists will be attracted to the participation of the benefits that will be offered to them,&quot; - says the document of urban planning.
Some transportation system designers, however, are wondering if all the talk of gratuity payments is just a huge distraction.
At the City Transportation Commission in the San Francisco Bay Area, officials say Congress could very easily overcome the bankruptcy of the Highway Building Trust by raising gas taxes.
An additional one-time or annual tax could be levied on hybrid drivers and others whose vehicles do not use a lot of gas to pay their fair share.
“There is no need for radical surgery when all you have to do is take an aspirin,” said Randy Rentschler, director of the Commission on Law and Public Relations.
If we do this, hundreds of millions of drivers will be worried about their privacy and a host of other things.
Pope Francis will name the first cardinals in February
Pope Francis will ordain the new cardinals of the Catholic Church for the first time in his term on February 22, the Vatican announced Thursday.
The cardinals are the highest clergy in the Catholic Church after the pope, and it is they who elect the popes, so that Francis will appoint his first group of people who will ultimately participate in the selection of his successor.
There are currently 201 cardinals.
However, after the cardinal reaches 80 years of age, he can no longer take part in the election of the pope - this is the prerogative of a group of 120 &quot;cardinals-electors&quot;.
Announcing the news, Vatican spokesman Father Federico Lombardi said that a meeting of all current cardinals, known as the consistory, would be held prior to the ordination ceremony.
“Pope Francis decided to communicate in advance his decision to convene the consistory in February in order to facilitate the scheduling of other meetings with cardinals from around the world,” Lombardi said.
Jack Valero of Catholic Voices said the number of cardinal electors is likely to decline by February.
He said that usually the pope names as many cardinals as necessary to bring the number of elective cardinals back to 120, as well as as many cardinals over the age of 80 as he wishes.
The consistory next year will go a long way because it will be the first since the election of Francis in March this year, according to Valero.
At the moment, there is a kind of bias in favor of Europe and especially in favor of Italy.
“It will be interesting to see if the new pope will appoint cardinals from other regions of the world to restore the balance,” he said.
Forty percent of Catholics live in South America, but they are represented by an insignificant number of cardinals.
They will also be the first elected cardinals since Francis formed the Council of Cardinals, a group of eight cardinals from around the world tasked with finding ways to reform the church.
In the past, dad decided everything himself.
“Now Francis has chosen eight cardinals to help him,” Valero said.
He said it was &quot;quite possible&quot; that Francis would turn to the cardinals for advice.
But we were not in such a situation before - all this for us for the first time.
Valero said that popes used to elevate bishops from large parishes to the office of cardinal, but Francis &quot;is full of surprises - so we do not know who he will name.&quot;
