Syria destroyed its chemical weapons manufacturing facilities, watchdog team says
Syria has destroyed basic chemical weapons and poison gas munitions, an international watchdog team said Thursday, as violent clashes raged in the north of the country, near one of the sites believed to contain toxic substances.
Also Thursday, a Syrian activist group said more than 120,000 people have been killed since the start of the country&#39;s civil war nearly three years ago.
The Organization for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons statement was made one day before
the November 1 deadline set by this Hague-based organization for Damascus to destroy or “render inoperative” all chemical weapons production and mechanisms that allow chemicals to be mixed into poison gas and filled with ammunition.
The completion of what is essentially the initial stage of destruction is an important milestone in an ambitious timetable that aims to destroy all Damascus chemical weapons by mid-2014.
The destruction of equipment means that Syria can no longer produce new chemical weapons.
Nonetheless, Damascus has yet to begin the destruction of existing weapons and stockpiles.
The country is believed to have around 1,000 metric tons of chemicals and weapons, including mustard gas and the nerve gas sarin.
The announcement came during fierce fighting on Thursday in the city of Safira, which experts say contains a chemical weapons production facility and storage sites, according to the UK-based Syrian Human Rights Center.
A group of activists that tracked losses through a network of activists in Syria said on Thursday that 120,296 people had died.
Of these, 61,067 were said to be civilians, including 6,365 children.
On the government side, the group said, 29,954 are members of President Bashar al-Assad&#39;s armed forces, 18,678 are pro-government fighters and 187 are Lebanese Hezbollah fighters.
Also among the dead, according to the statement, were 2,202 army defectors and about 5,375 opposition fighters, many of them foreigners.
According to a UN estimate dated July 25, 100,000 have died in the conflict since March 2011.
This figure has not been updated since then.
The conflict has forced about 2 million people to flee the country.
Assad&#39;s forces have fought for weeks in Safir with insurgents, many of whom are associated with al-Qaeda groups.
The center said there were casualties on both sides on Thursday, but did not provide specific details.
The fighting highlighted the dangers faced by chemical weapons inspectors, driven by the tight deadlines of their mission to rid Syria of its toxic arsenal, amid the ongoing civil war.
The OPCW, which works closely with the United Nations, said in a statement that its team was &quot;now satisfied that it has checked and seen destroyed all Syrian-declared critical production facilities and mixing / filling equipment.&quot;
She added that &quot;no additional inspection activities are currently planned.&quot;
Inspectors said earlier this week that they completed the first round of verification work, visiting 21 of the 23 sites Damascus has declared.
They were unable to visit two locations for security reasons, inspectors said.
On Thursday, the OPCW said both sites were, according to Syria, &quot;abandoned and ... the chemical weapons program items in them have been moved to other declared locations that have been verified.&quot;
It was not immediately possible to determine whether the Safir site was one of two locations that OPCW inspectors were unable to visit.
Syria has presented a plan for the complete destruction of its chemical weapons, which is to be approved next month by the OPCW&#39;s executive committee.
“I applaud the courage and bravery that you all have shown in carrying out the most challenging mission ever undertaken by this organization,” said Observatory Director General Ahmet Uzumcu in a comment posted by the OPCW.
For the third year in a row, the civil war has pitted insurgents, mostly Sunni Muslims, against the Assad government and its security forces, which are made up of members of his Alawite sect, an offshoot of Shia Islam.
In other developments, head of the center Rami Abdurrahman said there was a massive explosion on Wednesday at an air defense facility in Syria&#39;s coastal province of Latakia.
The cause of the explosion is unknown, he said.
