What will the construction of TPU in Moscow lead to?
Every year the city authorities promise to equip more and more transport interchange hubs (TPU).
By 2020, it is planned to commission 255 TPUs.
Our correspondent figured out what the project actually turns out to be.
A couple of months ago, a construction fence appeared near the Smolenskaya metro station of the Arbatsko-Pokrovskaya line.
The inscription said that the arrangement of the transport interchange hub was underway.
All this was very strange, since no ground transport stops near &quot;Smolenskaya&quot; and, therefore, it is impossible to change to it.
To get to the nearest trolleybus stop on the Garden Ring, you need to overcome about 130 meters, including the ground crossing over Karmanitsky Lane.
Now &quot;Smolenskaya&quot; is almost finished.
The flower stall has disappeared, the newspaper stand has been dismantled, and the asphalt in front of the entrance has been replaced by paving stones.
That&#39;s the whole transport hub.
Transport hubs are flat and capital, - explain in the press service of the Moscow Department of Transport.
There are no capital TPUs yet.
And flat ones involve the construction of parking lots, the withdrawal of shopping facilities that interfere with the movement of passengers, the creation of small architectural forms and landscaping.
Actually, it is not transport workers who are even engaged in flat-bed TPUs, but professional organizers from the Moscow Department of Overhaul.
A transport hub is not necessarily a complex structure, explains Mikhail Blinkin, director of the Institute for Transport Economics and Transport Policy at the Higher School of Economics.
Sometimes it is enough to have a roof over your head and a board informing you about the time of arrival of the vehicle.
For example, a fully-fledged plane transfer hub was recently opened near the Yasenevo metro station.
Even without awnings, but with intercepting parking lots and scoreboards indicating when the bus will come.
But in pursuit of the quantity, officials write down everything they hit at TPU.
Back in 2011, the mayor&#39;s office planned to build 151 nodes for everything, 59 of them with capital construction.
Now the plans until 2020 include as many as 255 TPUs.
Of these, one and a half hundred promise to pass this year.
Although the city has a program for the development of TPU, no quality criteria have been identified, - says Alexander Morozov, co-chairman of the public organization &quot;City and Transport&quot;.
They report on the number of objects, but the quality of transplantation at each of them often deteriorates.
According to the expert, there should be two criteria: firstly, reducing the transplant time, and secondly, convenience.
First of all, the ability to change the mode of transport without going out in the rain.
In Moscow, when arranging a TPU, it sometimes turns out exactly the opposite.
A striking example of the VDNKh metro station.
Previously, suburban buses from the Yaroslavskoe highway came to the square in front of the main entrance to the All-Russian Exhibition Center.
Now their stops have been moved to the opposite side of Yaroslavka to Kosmonavtov Street.
Farther from the metro, much farther from the monorail, but closer to residential buildings.
Even though the residents did not want the bus station under the windows at all and complained to all possible authorities.
Somehow it didn&#39;t work out right away with capital TPUs in Moscow.
The first of them began to be built about five years ago at the Planernaya metro station.
The project was intended to be exemplary.
And it really turned out to be an example of how a transfer hub, left to the mercy of investors, turns into a banal shopping center.
No, there are platforms for buses, a canopy to keep out of the subway in the rain, and three floors of parking lots.
True, Khimki trolleybuses # 202 and # 203 were not given a place in the Moscow TPU.
They, like strangers, were pushed away from the metro.
But there is more room for trade.
There are 32 stores alone, but in general there is almost everything - from pet supplies to a car dealership.
Well, in fact, what if any of the bus passengers need to buy a new car on the road?
When we build a capital TPU, for some reason we always get a shopping center.
Recently, the situation reached its logical conclusion, when it was decided to give part of the parking lot for the market.
Now, on the third floor of the Planernaya TPU, there is a brisk trade among the parking spaces marked on the floor.
Vegetables, spices, Chinese jeans, non-Russian language and security guards glaring at our photographer.
The transfer hub has finally turned into a bazaar.
The fact is that there used to be a market near the Planernaya metro station, but it was demolished.
And in the prefecture, the traders were sorry and let them into the intercepting parking lot of the interchange hub.
Anyway, due to high prices, it is always empty.
The funny thing is that the market was demolished in order to build in its place ... a new plane TPU.
Such is the castling.
At the Kaluzhskaya metro station, the approach distance from the metro lobby to the bus was 50 meters, ”says Alexander Morozov.
After the construction of a shopping center, supposedly a TPU, the distance increased to 170 meters.
To get on the bus, you need to walk through the entire shopping center.
After 22 hours, when it is closed, you have to go around it in the open air.
However, the structures at Planernaya and Kaluzhskaya will soon seem like flowers.
In mid-September, the city planning and land commission of the mayor&#39;s office approved the planning decisions for the first eight capital transport hubs.
Four of them will be 25-storey, not counting two or three underground levels.
The main monster will grow up near the Tushino metro station, it will have 418.7 thousand square meters. meters of area.
Representatives of the directorate of railway stations of Russian Railways, who are responsible for the construction of a TPU near the metro, have already told reporters: the future high-rise buildings will house shops, hotels and apartments.
At the same time, officials assure that multi-storey parking will occupy from a third to a half of the area.
Take people&#39;s garages as an example.
Let&#39;s say a garage for 258 cars, which was recently built on Mezhdunarodny Street, has an area of 8015 sq. meters.
This means that a parking lot for 2.6 thousand cars at Petrovsko-Razumovskaya will need about 80 thousand squares.
This is less than a third of the colossus they are going to build there.
Let one or two floors go to all sorts of bus platforms.
Remains at least 150 thousand square meters. meters of commercial real estate.
And this, for a minute, is almost two GUM.
If capital TPUs near stations and railway stations are built by railway workers, then the rest of the sites will be developed by metro workers.
They also promised that there will be many &quot;functional facilities&quot;, including hotels, offices and even gyms.
By the way, the Moscow City Property Department recently told reporters that they are developing a draft resolution, according to which investors will be able to apply for a land plot for TPU to officials directly.
Without any competitions.
Because, they say, transport issues are a priority for the city.
An ideal TPU is, for example, the Harvard station in Boston or the Spadine station in Toronto, - Alexander Morozov is sure.
There, trolleybuses and trams descend underground to the metro level and the approach distance from the metro car to the tram is only 50 meters without going outside.
There is no unnecessary trade around.
But he takes Moscow officials to extremes.
Either we won&#39;t build anything, or we&#39;ll have 25 floors with offices and apartments.
