Bombardier&#39;s profits decline as shipments and aircraft orders drop
Bombardier Corp., a Canadian aircraft and train manufacturer, reported a 15 percent cut in net profit on Thursday, impacted by declining orders and aircraft shipments in the third quarter and contract problems at its rail division.
Montreal-based Bombardier has also not released any flight test data for its newest CSeries aircraft, or provided new information on whether the aircraft&#39;s ambitious plans to enter commercial service by next September will be met.
Since the first flight of the prototype aircraft, which took place about a month and a half ago, it has flown only three more times, which raises questions about whether the testing phase is on schedule.
The results fell short of forecasts and led to shares falling more than 8 percent on the Toronto Stock Exchange.
Cameron Doerksen, an analyst at National Bank Financial, cut his estimate Thursday from above-market to “market-average” on the belief that stock gains will be limited in the next quarter or two.
“While the decline in aircraft shipments was generally predictable, we are certainly disappointed with the transport department&#39;s earnings performance,” Doerksen said in a stock market review.
We believe Bombardier will receive new orders for CSeries as the flight test program continues.
However, if no new orders are announced in the coming months, we expect the market to become more skeptical of the program.
Bombardier hopes the CSeries family of aircraft will allow it to gain a foothold in the lower-price segment of the market now dominated by Boeing and Airbus.
The first prototype aircraft was presented in March and flew for the first time in September after several months of delay.
However, there are still few firm orders for the CSeries at 177, as potential buyers await flight test results to validate the company&#39;s claims about fuel efficiency and potential economy of the new liner.
In total, there are now 403 orders and agreements with 15 clients and operators.
Chief Executive Officer Pierre Baudouin was confident that Bombardier would meet its target of 300 firm orders by the time the first aircraft went into commercial service.
Executives also reassured analysts and the media Thursday that the program is moving forward as planned.
&quot;The test aircraft did not stay on the ground longer than expected,&quot; Baudoin said during a conference call, adding that ground tests and software updates were planned during the aircraft&#39;s downtime.
All manufacturers plan tests differently.
We decided to make the first flight and take a break for updates, so we did.
This will continue throughout the flight test program.
The second of five test specimens is due to fly in the coming weeks, and the rest will follow shortly, the company said.
Still, analysts are skeptical about the claim that the first customer will be able to start operating the CSeries aircraft 12 months after its first flight.
Bombardier said it is evaluating the commissioning timeline and will provide new information in the next few months.
“This slow pace of flight testing - although it appears to be in line with Bombardier&#39;s internal schedule - reinforces our view that commissioning will be postponed to the first quarter of 2015,” Doerksen said.
In the third quarter ended September 30, Bombardier&#39;s net income fell to $ 147 million, or 8 cents a share, from $ 172 million, or 9 cents a share, last year.
Adjusted earnings per share remained the same at 9 cents.
Gross income decreased slightly - from $ 4.2 billion to $ 4.1 billion.
Analysts were expecting earnings of 10 cents a share and gross income of $ 4.56 billion, according to Thomson Reuters I / B / E / S.
The world&#39;s fourth-largest aircraft manufacturer reported that it delivered 45 aircraft in the quarter, down from 57 in the previous year.
The total number of orders fell from 83 to 26 aircraft.
Aerospace&#39;s order book was $ 32.9 billion as of September 30, unchanged from December 31.
“In aerospace, the results were in line with our goals, but the low order volume and general market conditions were an unpleasant factor,” Baudouin said.
Aerospace gross revenue fell 13 percent to $ 2 billion.
Bombardier, the world&#39;s largest train maker, reported that gross revenue in the sector rose nearly 11 percent to $ 2.1 billion.
The order book in the transportation division was $ 32.6 billion as of September 30, slightly higher than on December 31.
The transport division&#39;s earnings were negatively impacted by problems with the execution of several large contracts.
Management announced that a new development plan will be presented in the fourth quarter.
Bombardier, which also announced that Google Chief Financial Officer Patrick Picchett will join the board of directors, fell 8.5 percent to from $ 4.83 in mid-Thursday trading.
Brazilian company Embraer SA, the world&#39;s third-largest commercial aircraft manufacturer and closest competitor to Bombardier, reported a 10 percent decrease in quarterly revenue on Thursday.
