Two YMCA staff members have been charged with sex offenses prior to the charges against Jonathan Lord as reported to the Royal Commission
Two YMCA NSW employees were charged with child sex offenses prior to the 2011 charges against Karingbach childcare worker Jonathan Lord, the Royal Commission on Child Sexual Abuse reported.
But the commission&#39;s opening statement said that it &quot;has never dealt with child sexual abuse within its organization.&quot;
CEO Philippe Hare was asked about one case where a YMCA employee was charged with child pornography crimes and another case where a gym instructor at YMCA Caringbah Hall was convicted of sex crimes against children in his care in 1991. year.
Mr. Hare told Gail Furness, an attorney assisting the commission, that he knew about the first case but did not know about the second.
He acknowledged that the YMCA was also inaccurate in its opening speech to the commission, arguing that &quot;there were external YMCA reviews that found the YMCA to be at the forefront of child safety.&quot;
The evidence presented to the commission suggests that the YMCA was notified that it received the second-lowest out of four possible ratings in a quality audit performed by the Department of Education and Communities in August this year.
Mr. Hare, who joined the YMCA when he was 21, admitted that he and lower management blundered in hiring Lord, and failed to ensure that staff clearly understood their responsibilities regarding reporting child safety violations.
Earlier this year, Lord was convicted of sex crimes against 12 boys during his two years at the YMCA.
He was jailed for at least six years.
But Mr. Hare dismissed the suggestion that the YMCA&#39;s corporate ethics prevented employees from reporting Lord&#39;s child safety violations.
The officers testified that they observed violations, including the fact that Lord was alone with the children, personally looked after them, put them on his lap, said that he loved one of them and allowed them to play with his mobile phone.
Danielle Oakwell, who was under Lord&#39;s direction and asked to teach her child protection because she was worried about his behavior, testified that she found Jackie Barnath, the child custody manager of the YMCA in Karingbach, who was Lord&#39;s leader, “very frightening and often difficult to access &quot;.
The CEO said he would not accept employee explanations that they were embarrassed to report the situation to their superiors.
Rather, he said, their friendship with the Lord took them away from the thought of reporting him.
Mr. Hare said that he presented to the NSW YMCA his view that the lesson for organizing from the “Jonathan Lord incident” is not “about providing information” from the staff, and the board agreed with him.
Mr. Hare said the decision to force employees to sign confidentiality agreements shortly after the allegations were raised was made by YMCA Child Custody Director Liam Wheatley.
He said that this was intended to prevent corruption of evidence, but at the same time &quot;overdoing&quot; and this decision was poorly implemented.
The New South Wales YMCA was not a child-safe organization when Jonathan Lord was employed between 2009 and 2011, child molestation expert Professor Stephen Smallbone of Griffith University told the commission.
He said there were &quot;serious problems&quot; in recruiting, selecting, instructing, training and supervising personnel.
The hearings have been postponed until December 20.
