It can be safely argued that New York is the birthplace of stand-up comedy in America: almost a century ago, entertainer Frank Fay, who worked as an entertainer at the Palace Theater on Broadway, began telling jokes directly to the public in a conversational manner.
Fay&#39;s innovation was eventually picked up by others, most recently the New York Comedy Festival.
Created and curated by Caroline Hirsch, founder of the Carolines stand-up club, the festival celebrates its tenth anniversary this year with over sixty shows in small clubs and large theaters.
“Most of these headliners started out with the Carolines and then they got better, they got to the point where they’re too famous to be in the club,” said Hersch.
We created this festival as a way to continue working with them.
